# W1': a `|>` chain applied to a WHOLE value-position js` literal that itself
# carries a nested @{ } hole (Task 4's split target) — `wrap(js`f(@{x})` |>
# upper)`. The whole-literal pipe is NOT one of the literal's holes: it is a
# gsx pipe over the entire literal, which has no meaning in Go-expression
# position. The split scanner catches it purely syntactically (scanGoParts's
# PipeOff), positioned at the `|>`, BEFORE analyze.go's hole split or emit's
# assembleHoleSeed ever runs — so exactly one clean diagnostic surfaces, never
# a skeleton cascade. Contrast a pipe at a HOLE's own top level
# (`js`f(@{ f`x` |> upper })``, see nested_hole_pipe.txtar) which parsePipe
# strips into a normal hole Stage and is fully supported. No `wrap` definition
# is needed: the rejection is syntactic, before any name resolves.
-- input.gsx --
package demo

component Page() {
	<div>{ wrap(js`f(@{x})` |> upper) }</div>
}
-- invoke --
Page()
-- diagnostics.golden --
4:26: whole-literal pipelines are not supported in Go-expression position; wrap the literal in a function call instead
-- render.golden --
